Understanding How to Increase a Best Press

Background

Powerlifting is an olympic strength sport that depends on lifting as much weight as possible in the categories of bench press, squat, and deadlift. Powerlifters have 3 attempts at each exercise to lift the most weight possible which will then be accumulated for a total score. Powerlifters are also allowed equipment in order to help them lift more weight. The bench press is commonly the most favored exercise and many are searching to understand what accounts for an increase in the best bench press weight. Data was gathered from several power lifting competitions in order to understand this question further.

Pairs plot

A pairs plot shows the relationship between 2 variables. The interest is in seeing if there is a pattern within the pairs plot, a pattern will help us understand if there is a relationship between 2 variables. The top row has the best bench press as the y-axis for all of the plots. It seems that the best squat has the clearest and strongest relationship to the best bench press since it shows a clear straight line. Interestingly enough, the Wilks column doesnt show as much insight to a powerlifters bench press as expected. The Wilks is a way to measure the strength of a powerlifter and have them be compared to other powerlifters in different weight classes. Ultimately, the best squat of a powerlifter as well as a slight trend from the best deadlift appear to give the most insight into the best bench press of a powerlifter.

# What influences someones bench press?
pairs(power.data, panel = panel.smooth)

# Testing new lm equations

mydata2 <- mydata %>%
  filter(BestBenchKg > 0) %>%
  filter(BestSquatKg > 0) %>%
  filter(BestDeadliftKg > 0)

# Rsquared: 72.15
mylm <- lm(BestBenchKg ~ BestSquatKg
           + Sex
           + Equipment
           + BestSquatKg:Sex
          + BestSquatKg:Equipment
           ,data = mydata2)
#summary(mylm)

# Rsquared: 82.1

mylm <- lm(BestBenchKg ~ BestSquatKg
           + Sex
           + BestSquatKg:Equipment
           ,data = mydata2)
#summary(mylm)

Regression Model

Below is the mathematical model that represents what accounts for the best bench press of a lifter. Although it may be hard to understand initially, these are what each variables represent:

\(\hat{Y}_i\): represents the estimated best bench press from the given the regression equation

\(b_0\): represents the best bench press when the best squat is 0 kg

\(b_1\): represents the best squat of the lifter in kilograms

\(b_2\): represents the genders sex (this will cause the lines to differ in their intercepts)

\(b_3\): represents the interaction between the best squat of a lifter and their equipment used (this will cause the slopes to change between equipment used)

\[ \underbrace{\hat{Y}_i}_{\text{Best Bench (kg)}} = b_0 + b_1 \underbrace{X_{1i}}_{\text{Best Squat (kg)}} + b_2 \underbrace{X_{2i}}_{\text{Sex}} + b_3 \underbrace{X_{1i} X_{4i}}_{\text{Best Squat (kg) * Equipment}} + \epsilon_i \]

The above mathematical equation will be used to estimate a powerlifters best bench press given their best squat, sex, and equipment used. This model is an estimate of the mathematical model below, which came from the data given in the data set:

\[ \underbrace{{Y}_i}_{\text{Best Bench (kg)}} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \underbrace{X_{1i}}_{\text{Best Squat (kg)}} + \beta_2 \underbrace{X_{2i}}_{\text{Sex}} + \beta_3 \underbrace{X_{3i} X_{4i}}_{\text{Best Deadlist (kg) * Equipment}} + \epsilon_i \]

The mathematical model above represents the same data. However, this mathematical model represents the data observed. The larger Bs found in the model are called betas and represent the true mathematical model that accounts for a powerlifters best bench press. However, these are estimated in the model above by the b values. Continually, youll notice that there is an \(\epsilon_i\) at the end of this model, this is called an epsilon which causes the data points to deviate away from the regression line, think of this as errors since they arent always perfectly on the regression line.

Hypothesis & Model Summary

Testing the Slope of the Baseline

To assume that \(b_1\) is 0 would mean that there is no relationship between the best bench (kg) and best squat (kg) of a powerlifter. However, to gain further insight in the standards of these lifters, \(b_1\) will be tested at 0.25, this is to understand if there is a significant relationship between both variables, being the best bench press and best squat of the lifters. 0.25 will be used to test the slope to understand if this assumed linear relationship between these 2 variables is true. This hypothesis will be tested with the significance level of \(\alpha=0.05\). As displayed below in the summary table, the p-value given is <2e-16, however this was under the assumption that the slope if different than 0. The p-value given when tested against 0.25 is 0.0001275859. Since this value is lower than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. This is because the estimate for the relationship or slope is 0.6365065 which differs significantly from 0.25.

\[ H_0: \beta_1 = 0.25 \quad \text{(Best Bench & Best Squat have no significant relationship)} \\ H_a: \beta_1 \neq 0.25 \quad \text{(Best Bench & Best Squat have a significant relationship)} \]

Understanding the Y-int

The estimate given for the y-int is -3.18 (represented by \(b_0\)) with a p-value less than 2e-16 which is less than 0.05 meaning that its also considered significant. However, the y-int for this regression isnt interpretable since its not reasonable for someone to squat 0 pounds or bench press negative weight as a powerlifter.

Testing the Interaction of Squat to Raw Equipment

\(b_3\) being 0 would imply that the slope of best squat for those with raw equipment does not differ from that of multiply equipment. \(b_3\) not being 0 would imply that the slope for best squat for those with raw equipment does differ from those with multiply equipment. As displayed below in the summary table, the p-value is <2e-16 which is significantly less than 0.05 meaning that the relationship of best bench press and best squat differ for both groups of equipment used. Continually, the estimate below is displayed as -0.0330829. This represents how much the relationship differs from the multiply line, in other words the slope for those who squatted with raw equipment is -0.0330829 less than that of multiply.

\[ H_0: \beta_3 = 0 \quad \text{(Equal rates growth)} \\ H_a: \beta_3 \neq 0 \quad \text{(Non-equal rates of growth)} \]

Testing the Interaction of Squat to Singleply Equipment

\(b_4\) being 0 would imply that the slope of best squat for those with singeply equipment does not differ from that of multiply equipment. \(b_4\) not being 0 would imply that the slope for best squat for those with singeply equipment does differ from those with multiply equipment. As displayed below in the summary table, the p-value is <2e-16 which is significantly less than 0.05 meaning that the relationship of best bench press and best squat differs for both groups of equipment used. Continually, the estimate below is displayed as -0.0644137. This represents how much the relationship differs from the multiply line. Its important to recognize that even though \(b_4\) was not displayed in the regression equation above, this is incorporated into \(b_3\) in the regression equation since that is the variable that changes the slope depending on the equipment used, however the independent change from multiply to singely was tested for \(b_4\).

\[ H_0: \beta_4 = 0 \quad \text{(Equal rates growth)} \\ H_a: \beta_4 \neq 0 \quad \text{(Non-equal rates of growth)} \]

Testing the Interaction of Squat to Wraps Equipment

\(b_5\) being 0 would imply that the slope of best squat for those with wraps equipment does not differ from that of multiply equipment. \(b_5\) not being 0 would imply that the slope for best squat for those with wraps equipment does differ from those with multiply equipment. As displayed below in the summary table, the p-value is <2e-16 which is significantly less than 0.05 meaning that the relationship of best bench press and best squat differ for both groups of equipment used. Continually, the estimate below is displayed as -0.0454318. This represents how much the relationship differs from the multiply line. Its important to recognize that even though \(b_5\) was not displayed in the regression equation above, this is incorporated into \(b_3\) in the regression equation since that is the variable that changes the slope depending on the equipment used, however the independent change from multiply to wraps was tested for \(b_5\).

\[ H_0: \beta_5 = 0 \quad \text{(Equal rates growth)} \\ H_a: \beta_5 \neq 0 \quad \text{(Non-equal rates of growth)} \]

## F-statistic: 2.629e+05 on 5 and 286639 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Above is the results of the statistical test that will help us understand more about what accounts for the best bench press of a power lifter. The estimate for the intercept shows us what the prediction for the best bench press is when the best squat is 0. Continually, the best squat tells us the change in the average best bench press for each powerlifter. In other words, for every 0.63kg increase in the best squat, the best bench press increases by 1kg. Continually, the Pr(>|t|) column has the p-values which shows us the significance of each variable in the regression model. Since they are below 0.05, this means that they are considered statistically significant. The column named Std. Error represents the standard error for each variable. This tells us how much the results of this statistical test may differ from other samples, attempting to replicate the same results with different data. In essence, since the standard error seems to be small for all of the variables, the results should be trusted since they are likely to be replicated across more samples of data.

Continually, on the bottom is the residual standard error. This is a measure of the overall deviation or error between the predicted values (found on the regression line) and the actual observed values in a linear regression model. It represents the average amount of variability in the response variable that is not explained by the model. A lower RSE indicates that the model fits the data better, whereas a higher RSE indicates that the model may not be capturing all of the important factors that influence the y-variable, being the best bench press. The residual standard error is 20.26 as shown in the summary table above. This means that 20.26(kg) is the average amount that the data deviates from the estimated regression line.

Lastly, at the bottom right of this table is the adjusted r-squared. R-squared is a measure that tells us how well a line (or curve) fits a set of data. It ranges from 0 to 1, with 1 being the best possible fit. A higher r-squared value means that the line is a better predictor of the data, but it may not always mean that the line causes the data. The r-squared is shown to be 0.821 which is considerably high and means that 82.1% of the variability observed in the best bench press is explained by the regression model above. In other words, this tells us how well the data fit the regression and it appears to be a good fit!

Visualizing the Model

my.pred1 <- predict(mylm, newdata=data.frame(BestSquatKg = 140,
                                              Sex='M',

               aes(x=x,y=y,yend=yend,xend=xend),inherit.aes=FALSE, col = 'white') +
  geom_segment(data=data.wrap,
               aes(x=x,y=y,yend=yend,xend=xend),inherit.aes=FALSE, col = 'white') +
  labs(x = "Best Squat (Kg)", y = "Best Bench (Kg)") +

  scale_linetype_discrete(name = "Sex") +

  theme_classic()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Above is the graph of the model. The y-axis represents the bench bench press in kilograms for each lifter and the x-axis represents the best squat in kilograms for each lifter. Each line also represents a different equipment used since they are understood to vary from one another. For further context, multiply is multiple layers of supportive material worn by the lifter, raw means that no equipment was used, single-ply refers to one piece of supportive material used such as a lifting belt or knee sleeves, and wraps refers to wrist wraps.

The lines you see on the graph are the regression lines and give us an estimate of the best bench press that a lifter will achieve, based on their best squat. Continually, youll notice that there are vertical white line on the black regression lines, these are prediction intervals. Prediction intervals give us a range of values that an observation is likely to fall within, based on the data and the model used to make the prediction. They take into account the variability in the data and the accuracy of the model, and provide an estimate of the range of possible outcomes, rather than just a single point estimate. They are corresponding to the higher or steeper line since these are the lines that represent the male powerlifters. These prediction intervals are telling what the predicted best bench press is for a man with a 140 kg squat for each different lifting equipment.

Verifying the Model

When it comes to verifying the model, there are 5 assumptions that must be verified for the linear regression model. Including: (1) The regression relationship between X & Y is linear. (2) The error terms are normally distributed with \(E\{\epsilon_i\}=0\) (3)The variance of the error terms is constant over all X values (4) the X values can be considered fixed and measured without error. and (5 ) the error terms are independent

Below are plots that can be used to verify the above assumptions for linear regression models.

 plot(mylm, which = 1:2)

 plot(mylm$residuals)

In the first plot, we are looking to see that there are no clear patterns. We are looking to see that the dots are evenly dispersed above and below the line as well as have no clear shape. The horizontal line at 0 represents the regression line and the points represent the residuals and how much they deviate from the regression. (Note: The red line in the middle goes through the middle of the data points). There appears to be a downward trend on the bottom of the red line however this doesnt appear to be too dramatic, as the red line continues to keep a straight line as well. This means that the regression relationship between the best squat and best bench press is linear and that the variance of error terms is constant over all best squat values.

In the second plot, we are looking to see that the data points are as close to the dotted line as possible. These points are whats called residuals which in essence are the distance from the actual data points observed to the estimated line (the black lines that are in the model above). If these data points clearly follow the dotted line, this means that the error terms are normally distributed (since the residuals are in essence the models error). It appears that both ends of the line deviate from the dotted line a fair amount. This would imply that the data is heavy tailed meaning that there are a lot of outliers on either end of the data (low or high). This means that there are several observations that are much larger than the rest of the data. However, this shouldnt invalidate the results of the test since it helps us understand that the residuals are larger on either end of the regression line.

Lastly, in the third plot, we are looking to see that there is no clear trend or shape. This plot is to verify that the error terms are independent from one another. There appear to no be any but a line that comes from the 286,639 observations. This implies that the independent error terms assumption is valid.

With a further understanding of these assumptions and their qualifications, it can be assumed that the regression given is a good fit for the data and will help in our understanding in what accounts for a powerlifters best bench press.

Conclusion

In conclusion it appears that squatting and equipment accounts for the biggest differences in increasing someones bench press. This is likely because of the overall strength of the powerlifter and the incorporation of compound exercises in their workouts which include the bench press and squat. Continually, the equipment also reflects the overall utilities that powerlifters use in their training to help them lift more weight. Thus its essential that a powerlifter utilizes their use of equipment, especially multiply as well as work on their overall strength in their squat in order to improve their bench press.
